aders within their historical context: Booker T. Washington, W. E. B. Du Bois, Marcus Garvey, A. Philip Randolph, Malcolm X, Martin Luther King, and many others. The work also describes the shift in emphasis in the movement from legal cases brought before the courts to mass protest movements and, later, the change in direction from civil rights to Black Power and, later, Pan-Africanism. Far more than just a history of civil rights leaders, this book explains how the achievements of African-American writers, artists, singers, and athletes contributed to a wider understanding of the humanity and culture of black Americans. Cashman details, among others, the achievements of the Harlem Renaissance, the films of Paul Robeson and Marian Anderson, and the works of Langston Hughes, Ralph Ellison, James Baldwin, and Toni Morrison. Written in an engaging style, the text is accompanied by a wealth of illustrations, some well known, others in print for the first time.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 0aAfrican AmericansxCivil rights. 0aCivil rights movementszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aCivil rights workerszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aRacismzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 4aAfrican-American. 4aAmericans. 4aThis. 4aachievements. 4aartists. 4aathletes. 4ablack. 4abook. 4acontributed. 4aculture. 4aexplains. 4ahumanity. 4asingers. 4aunderstanding. 4awider. 4awriters. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Discrimination & Race Relations.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814723593423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780814723593.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK